Title: The Yellow Wallpaper
Credit: Written by
Author: Charlotte Perkins Gilman
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/21/2025
Notes: Period live-action, late nineteenth century; gothic domestic atmosphere; restrained naturalistic performances. The NARRATOR is a young woman in her late twenties, pale, slender, dark hair simply dressed, in modest summer waists and skirts that grow rumpled as her condition worsens. JOHN is a practical physician in his mid-thirties, neat beard or clean-shaven, confident carriage, dark professional suits. JENNIE is John's sister, capable, neatly aproned, warm but firm. The yellow wallpaper is a sickly sulphur-and-orange sprawl with a strangling arabesque; barred windows; a heavy nailed-down bed.

===

EXT. COLONIAL MANSION - DAY

A hereditary estate set well back from the road: hedges, locking gates, broken greenhouses, a large shady garden with box-bordered paths and grape-covered arbors. The house stands empty-looking, handsome, and wrong.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It is very seldom that mere ordinary people like John and myself secure ancestral halls for the summer. A colonial mansion, a hereditary estate—I would say a haunted house, and reach the height of romantic felicity—but that would be asking too much of fate. Still I will proudly declare that there is something queer about it.

JOHN helps the NARRATOR down from a carriage. She pauses, looking up at the facade. He smiles, indulgent, already assessing the air and the grounds.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Else why should it be let so cheaply? And why have stood so long untenanted?

INT. MANSION HALL - DAY

Sunlight, dust, a long stair. JENNIE directs a trunk. Somewhere a baby fusses; MARY soothes it offscreen.

JOHN
Perfect rest. All the air you can get. That is the whole cure.

NARRATOR
I wanted the room downstairs—the one with the roses on the window.

JOHN
Drafty. One window. No room for two beds. We take the nursery at the top of the house.

He is already moving her toward the stairs, careful and loving, hand at her elbow.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

A big airy room, nearly the whole floor. Windows look all ways—and they are barred. Rings and things in the walls. A great heavy bed. The paint and paper are stripped in great patches around the head of the bed and low on the opposite wall.

The wallpaper that remains is a sprawling flamboyant pattern: dull yet lurid orange in places, a sickly sulphur tint in others—a smouldering unclean yellow.

The NARRATOR stands in the center, turning slowly.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I never saw a worse paper in my life. One of those sprawling flamboyant patterns committing every artistic sin. It is dull enough to confuse the eye in following, pronounced enough to constantly irritate. The color is repellant, almost revolting.

JOHN throws open a window.

JOHN
Air you can absorb all the time. Your exercise depends on your strength, my dear, and your food somewhat on your appetite.

NARRATOR
John—could we not paper it over?

JOHN
After the wallpaper it would be the bedstead, then the bars, then the gate at the head of the stairs. Nothing is worse for a nervous patient than to give way to fancies. We came here solely on your account. Three months. I do not care to renovate the house for a summer rental.

He kisses her forehead.

JOHN
You know the place is doing you good.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

Days later. The NARRATOR sits by a window with a small hidden portfolio, writing in stealth. Below: the delicious garden, mysterious arbors, a shaded lane toward a private wharf and the bay.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
John is a physician, and perhaps—I would not say it to a living soul, of course, but this is dead paper and a great relief to my mind—perhaps that is one reason I do not get well faster. You see, he does not believe I am sick. My brother says the same. So I take phosphates or phosphites, whichever it is, and tonics, and journeys, and air, and exercise, and am absolutely forbidden to work until I am well again.

Footsteps on the stair. She slides the portfolio under the bedclothes.

JOHN enters with a glass and a schedule-face.

JOHN
Lying down. Good. I have a prescription for each hour. Hardly let you stir without direction.

NARRATOR
I meant to be such a help to you.

JOHN
You are my darling and my comfort. Use your will. Do not let silly fancies run away with you.

He checks her pulse, satisfied that there is “no reason” to suffer, and goes. She pulls the writing out again, exhausted by the slyness.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Personally I believe that congenial work, with excitement and change, would do me good. But what is one to do?

EXT. GARDEN - DAY

The NARRATOR walks slowly the box-bordered paths. JENNIE cuts flowers, cheerful, watching her from a distance.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
There is a delicious garden. I never saw such a garden. I always fancy I see people walking in these numerous paths and arbors—but John has cautioned me not to give way to fancy in the least.

A flicker—almost a stooped figure—under the grape arbor. She blinks. Only leaves.

INT. NURSERY - NIGHT

Moonlight crawls in by one window then another. JOHN sleeps in the heavy bed. The NARRATOR lies awake staring at the wall.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
There is a recurrent spot where the pattern lolls like a broken neck and two bulbous eyes stare at you upside down. Up and down and sideways they crawl, and those absurd unblinking eyes are everywhere.

She rises softly, crosses, and touches the paper to see if it moves. Behind her JOHN wakes.

JOHN
What is it, little girl? Don’t go walking about like that—you’ll get cold.

NARRATOR
I am not gaining here. I wish you would take me away.

JOHN
Why, darling—our lease will be up in three weeks. The repairs are not done at home. Of course if you were in any danger I could and would, but you really are better, dear, whether you can see it or not. I am a doctor, dear, and I know.

NARRATOR
I don’t weigh a bit more, nor as much. My appetite may be better in the evening when you are here, but it is worse in the morning when you are away.

JOHN
(hugging her)
Bless her little heart—she shall be as sick as she pleases. Now let us improve the shining hours by going to sleep.

NARRATOR
And you won’t go away?

JOHN
How can I, dear? Three weeks more, then a nice little trip while Jennie gets the house ready. Really, you are better.

NARRATOR
Better in body perhaps—

He sits up, stern, reproachful.

JOHN
My darling, I beg of you, for my sake and for our child’s sake, as well as for your own, that you will never for one instant let that idea enter your mind. There is nothing so dangerous, so fascinating, to a temperament like yours. It is a false and foolish fancy. Can you not trust me as a physician when I tell you so?

She says nothing more. He settles. She lies awake, eyes on the undulating pattern.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I lay there for hours trying to decide whether that front pattern and the back pattern really did move together or separately.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

Harsh daylight. The NARRATOR traces the pattern from the untouched corner, hour after hour, on the immovable bed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
On a pattern like this, by daylight, there is a lack of sequence, a defiance of law, that is a constant irritant. You think you have mastered it, but just as you get well under way it turns a back-somersault and there you are. It slaps you in the face, knocks you down, and tramples upon you. It is like a bad dream.

JENNIE enters with tonics. The NARRATOR hides nothing quickly enough; JENNIE’s glance finds the portfolio.

JENNIE
I verily believe it is the writing which made you sick. Rest. John says sleep all you can.

NARRATOR
I will rest.

When JENNIE leaves, the NARRATOR does not sleep. She watches the sub-pattern.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
In certain lights I can see a strange, provoking, formless sort of figure that seems to sulk about behind that silly and conspicuous front design. Behind that outside pattern the dim shapes get clearer every day. It is always the same shape, only very numerous. And it is like a woman stooping down and creeping about behind that pattern.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

Fourth of July aftermath. The house quieter. The NARRATOR alone, fretting, crying without sound, then forcing stillness when steps approach.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
John says if I don’t pick up faster he shall send me to Weir Mitchell in the fall. I don’t want to go there at all. I cry at nothing, and cry most of the time. Of course I don’t when John is here. I am alone a good deal just now.

She stands close to the wall. The unclean yellow seems to breathe.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
This paper looks to me as if it knew what a vicious influence it had.

EXT. SHADED LANE - DAY

The NARRATOR on the porch under roses, then walking the lane. Far off, among blackberry vines and dark arbors, a woman creeps—stooped, deliberate. The NARRATOR stares, riveted, not afraid so much as recognized.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I think that woman gets out in the daytime. I can see her out of every one of my windows. It is the same woman, I know, for she is always creeping, and most women do not creep by daylight. I see her on that long road under the trees—and when a carriage comes she hides. I don’t blame her a bit.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

The NARRATOR locks the door. Alone, she creeps a little along the wall herself—testing, low, half-ashamed—then stops, listening for JOHN.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I always lock the door when I creep by daylight. I can’t do it at night, for I know John would suspect something at once. I don’t want anybody to get that woman out at night but myself.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

JENNIE’s hand is on the wallpaper. The NARRATOR has come in quietly.

NARRATOR
What are you doing with the paper?

JENNIE spins, angry and caught.

JENNIE
Why should you frighten me so? The paper stains everything it touches. Yellow smooches on all your clothes and John’s. Do be more careful.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Did not that sound innocent? But I know she was studying that pattern, and I am determined that nobody shall find it out but myself.

INT. DINING ROOM / HALL / STAIR - DAY

Fog and rain weather. The NARRATOR moves through the house; a yellow smell seems to hover, skulk, lie in wait. She lifts a lock of her hair as if it clings there.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
There is something else about that paper—the smell. It creeps all over the house. Even when I go to ride, if I turn my head suddenly—there is that smell. The only thing I can think of that it is like is the color of the paper. A yellow smell.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

Low down near the mopboard, a long straight even smooch runs round the room, behind every piece of furniture except the bed—rubbed over and over.

The NARRATOR follows it on her knees, dizzy, round and round.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I wonder how it was done and who did it and what they did it for. Round and round and round—it makes me dizzy.

INT. NURSERY - NIGHT

Moonlight. The outside pattern becomes bars. Behind them the woman is plain: shaking the pattern, taking hold of the bars, trying to climb through.

The NARRATOR watches, rapt, from the bed, JOHN asleep beside her.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The front pattern does move—and no wonder! The woman behind shakes it. Sometimes I think there are a great many women behind, and sometimes only one. She is all the time trying to climb through. But nobody could climb through that pattern—it strangles so.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

JOHN examines her with professional brightness. She smiles back, secret.

JOHN
You seem to be flourishing in spite of your wallpaper.

NARRATOR
(laughing it off)
Am I?

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I had no intention of telling him it was because of the wallpaper—he would make fun of me. He might even want to take me away. I don’t want to leave now until I have found it out.

JOHN
A week more. Then home.

He leaves for town cases. She turns at once to the wall, alive with purpose.

INT. NURSERY - NIGHT

The last nights. JOHN is to stay in town overnight. JENNIE at the door.

JENNIE
I could sleep with you.

NARRATOR
I shall undoubtedly rest better for a night all alone.

JENNIE goes, dubious. Moonlight. The woman in the paper crawls and shakes the pattern.

The NARRATOR rises and runs to help her.

She pulls. The figure seems to shake. She shakes and pulls. Wallpaper tears—yards of it—peeling in a strip as high as her head and half around the room. Yellow dust and scraps on the floor, under her nails, on her dress.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I pulled and she shook, I shook and she pulled, and before morning we had peeled off yards of that paper.

INT. NURSERY - DAY

Morning. The awful pattern seems to laugh in the sun. The NARRATOR, hair loose, face intent, works at the rest of it bare-handed and with a bit of bedstead.

NARRATOR
I declared I would finish it today.

JENNIE enters with moving baskets—furniture is to go back downstairs; they leave tomorrow. JENNIE stops, amazed at the stripped wall.

NARRATOR
(merrily)
I did it out of pure spite at the vicious thing.

JENNIE
I wouldn’t mind doing it myself—but I wouldn’t have had you tire yourself so. John will be out this evening.

JENNIE begins to move a small table. The NARRATOR watches her go, then locks the door when she is alone again. She throws the key down onto the front path under an open barred window.

INT. NURSERY - LATER DAY

The bed is the last great thing. She tugs; it will hardly move—nailed down. She abandons it and returns to the wall, peeling, creeping as she works, shoulder to the yellow.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Life is very much more exciting now than it used to be. You see I have something more to expect, to look forward to, to watch.

She pauses, listening to the house. Smiles.

NARRATOR
I wonder if they all come out of that wallpaper as I did?

INT. NURSERY - EVENING

Sunset and then lamp-less dusk. The room is a wreck of torn paper. The NARRATOR creeps on all fours along the smooch-line, shoulder brushing the wall, round and round. Her skirt is stained yellow. She does not stop.

Outside: carriage. JOHN’s voice in the hall, then at the locked door.

JOHN
Open the door, my darling!

NARRATOR
(creeping, calm)
I can’t. The key is down by the front steps, under a plantain leaf.

Amazement, then hurry on the stair. After a time the key scrapes in the lock. JOHN bursts in—and freezes.

The NARRATOR continues her circuit, creeping smoothly, eyes bright and empty-full.

NARRATOR
I’ve got out at last. In spite of you and Jane. And I’ve pulled off most of the paper, so you can’t put me back!

JOHN stares. Color leaves his face. He faints across her path, along the wall.

She reaches him without rising. Her shoulder and skirt pass over him as she creeps on, steady, around and around the nursery, following the long straight smooch where the woman got free.

NARRATOR
(soft, practically to herself)
It is so pleasant to be out in this great room and creep around as I please.

She creeps over him again on the next circuit as the light dies on the strangled yellow scraps.

FADE OUT.

END.
